Trends in travel prices since 1989
Prior to 1989, only five government tourism agencies could work in the former Czechoslovakia: žedok, Sporturist, CKM, Rekrea and Autoturist.
Since travel to the West was severely limited, tourists at that time mainly sold tours to the countries of the socialist bloc.
Thus, Czech tourists travelled to the German Democratic Republic for holidays; the Soviet Union (Sochi, Krym on the Black Sea); Bulgaria; Romania (either country on the Black Sea); and Hungary (Baladon).
The only exception was from 1962 to 1972, when we had the opportunity to travel to Yugoslavia, and then the Yugoslav regime returned to the West, resulting in considerable restrictions on the travel of Czech tourists to Yugoslavia.
The great paradox of the socialist period was that the citizens of the socialist bloc (i.e. Czechoslovakia) were not allowed individual visits to socialist countries.
If a citizen of Czechoslovakia wanted to go by himself, for example, to the Soviet Union or Poland, a letter of invitation was needed from that country; it was not possible to travel individually.
At the time, tourism agencies offered to travel to the West, but they had to either stand in line all night, with a sleeping bag, or have good friends in the agency.
And that was not all.
Currency permits were needed to travel to the West, not to be issued to politically unreliable people who were not allowed to travel at all.
The Czechoslovak currency was not freely converted; without currency permit it was impossible to obtain funds (western currencies) for travel to the West.
Most of the Czechs had spent their vacations at home, leading to a large number of cottages and summer homes, and this habit has continued to this day.
Since 1989, tourism in Czech Republic has thus experienced the present revolution.
While before 1989 the GDR or Bulgarian leave was the culmination of our trips, the Czechs held 4.5 million leaves in countries around the world last year.
The great paradox, which we no longer realize, is that until 1989, we were unable to visit Croatia, the most popular of all, since it was part of the former Yugoslavia.
At the beginning of 1990, the need to obtain a visa to neighbouring Western European countries had been lifted, leading to a huge wave of short journeys, mainly to Vienna and Germany.
The Czechoslovaks couldn't get rid of the West, and everyone wanted to go there for a moment.
For example, in Paris, Czech tourists slept in parks in tents because their income at that time was not enough for a hotel or boarding room.
A typical feature of Czech tourism during that period was the desire to bring its own food (conservations, salts, etc.) to save money.
Another important point is the introduction of a free-converted Czech crown, and after decades, our tourists are finally able to buy a western currency freely.
Our standard of living and average income grew, which led to another important situation about 1997.
Since 1997, increased demand has enabled tourism agencies to prepare regular flights carried out by charter airlines.
By the end of the 1990s, there was no need for visas to visit virtually all developed world countries except the United States, which made our journeys even easier.
The next significant event in the history of the post- revolution took place in 2000, with a great demand leading to the historic first direct charter flight from the Czech Republic to the exotic country, Thailand.
Since then, direct charter flights have brought Czech to the warm exotic countries, with 12 exotic flights from the Czech Republic in the winter.
Currently, about 100,000 Czechs are visiting exotic countries every year!
Another important event of this period, symbolizing our development after the revolution, took place in 2008.
On 17 November 2008, the United States abolished the need to obtain visas for Czech tourists, and our country thus joined the most developed world countries forever.
For the first time in history, in 2008, the Czechs spent more than half of their leaves abroad (50.3 per cent); for the first time in history, they spent over 15,000 kroner per person for leave abroad, including their costs at destination.
