“I also do not believe that if that happened, it would have an impact on the autonomy of the regulator,” and recalled that State policy planning in strategic areas, such as the telecommunications sector, is relevant to the federal executive power, which has a constitutional mandate, government administration.
The replacement of analogue signals to digital is one of the most important changes that have taken place in recent years has resulted in better use of the radio electric spectrum, better quality of the signal and more channels.
The postponement of the transition, he said, would mean deferring the benefits of converting to digital form, which includes meeting public needs, which has not only technical dimensions, “because it covers economic, social, political and national security issues”.
He said that “the entire system, established by the principle of public economic governance, is required to include a group of authorities, which the Constitution brings together the executive power”.
He recalled that a large number of countries around the world had already completed the transition to digital broadcasting and had done so through the executive, despite the existence of narrow technical institutions.
It could not be concluded that the Government, in adopting the decree under discussion, which in any case affected the competence of the Congress, ensured, in the administrative sphere, compliance with the laws adopted by the Legislative Assembly, he said.
