Why is unemployment so high among disabled workers?
Approximately 19 per cent of persons with disabilities are looking for work.
The 15th week of employment of disabled persons begins today.
Despite public charity policies launched in 2005, the proportion of persons with disabilities is still twice as high as the average, 19 per cent as against 9 per cent for the population as a whole.
Disgusting?
"No," stresses Eric Blanche, Director General Adapt, organization that organizes a week of employment for persons with disabilities.
“In 15 years, significant progress has been made.”
"The share of the unemployed was not 2, but 3 times more."
"There's still a lot of work ahead."
It must be said that there are still many barriers to employment for the disabled.
Among them, there are more older persons: 37 per cent over 50 years of age (17 per cent on the average).
They are more likely to have low qualifications: 80 per cent do not have a bachelor degree, and of 2.3 million higher education students, only 10,000 persons with disabilities.
Finally, long-term unemployment is widespread, which is 85 per cent for persons with disabilities, against the average of 38 per cent.
In short, these are all the criteria that make return to work very difficult and which constitute the essence of the problem”, according to Christian Grapen, Director-General of Tremplin, an association established in 1992 to help companies hire disabled workers.
These are some of the obstacles.
There is no need to talk about mentality that is changing, but too slow.
A study carried out in April by the IMS-Entrependre commissioned by Cité revealed that the managers interviewed had a low level of knowledge about disability and “represented persons in wheelchairs or mentally or mentally inexperienced persons”.
The result is that private companies with more than 20 employees are still far from having 6 per cent of the disabled workers set out in the 1987 Act.
The latest known figures for 2008 represent 2.6 per cent.
"Today we're about 3%," says Pierre Blan, Director General Agefiph, the organization responsible for collecting taxes from companies that do not comply with this law.
Evidence: The number of “contained” organizations, like the amounts paid, declined from 59,000 to 46,000 organizations in 2007-2011 (and from 606 to 480 million euros).
"The 2005 Act that raised the tax created strong pressure on companies, explains Pierre Blan."
“But this improvement also reflects increased consciousness, in particular in large enterprises.”
According to the Ministry of Employment, only 59 per cent of employees aged 20 to 49 have disabled workers, compared with 82 per cent of workers from 100 to 199.
